a node is a .human file and the filesystem is the whole dag, so progs/sort.human is a root, progs/sort/1.human is its child and the directory of the same name is the parent,

but every one of those relations is read off the path string alone and never off what happens to exist on disk, because a node names a place whether or not anyone has written it yet: 

Node('progs/sort/1/2') is constructed from that slash separated path, its file() is that path with .human under ROOT, 

its name() is the last segment, 

its level() is its depth below the root of its program so that a root is level 0, 

its parent() is the path with the last segment removed or None once only the program is left, 

its program() is the first two segments, 

its ancestors() run root first, 

its children() are the .human files in its directory ordered by their numeric names, 

its subtree() is itself followed by each child's subtree, 

its text() is the file stripped or empty when there is no file, 

and its intent() and assertions() split that text into the human sentence and the executable claims,

a claim being a line beginning 'assert:', which is cut out of the intent and therefore out of every prompt the model ever sees, so that a claim can only be tested and never taught to;
